Introduction
edition, Dravidian Etymological Dictionary Revised (DEDR) was published in 1984. This book
is a handy reference for researchers of Kannada and other Dravidian languages, to find the corres-
ponding forms in cognate languages. It is also made available in the internet for quick reference.
Kittel's Kannada English Dictionary
Kittel's Kannada English dictionary (1893) was written with great academic interest. It in-
cluded the old Kannada vocabulary also in a large quantity. The size of this dictionary is the
largest of all the dictionaries written by the other missionaries. He collected the material from
manuscripts also because the published books of old Kannada were a few at that time. Unfor-
tunately, Kittel has not mentioned the name of the source where from he got the manuscripts,
used by him. Now it is much more difficult to identify the source. Subsequently, most of the
manuscripts are published. But we have maintained the Kittel's version in order to highlight his
editorial policy. The Kittels dictionary was revised and enlarged by M. Mariappa Bhat, and it was
published in 4 volumes by the University of Madras, in 1968. We have used the revised edition of
the Kittel's dictionary also. The Kittel's dictionary as published in the original form in 1893 and
its revised edition published in 1968 are very useful for the students and researchers even today.
Kittel did not include in his dictionary the words containing letters ra (8) and ļa(®), if the
same words appeared in old Kannada, with ra (@) and ra (@9), possibly to avoid repetition. For
example kuri (700) “sheep” and kūļa (798) “rough and mean person” are not available in his
dictionary. The readers are expected to know that ra () part of the former word in old Kannada
was ra () and the part of ļa (5) in the other word, was in old Kannada ra (@9) respectively.
Therefore, the readers must open kuri (FIG) for kuri (F08) “sheep” and kūra (ESC) for kūļa (FS-
$5) “rough and mean person”. Then only they can find the word kuri (F08) in the form kuri (F3C%)
"sheep” and kūļa (788) in kūra (7809) respectively. Sometimes he was compelled to decide
which form should be included in the dictionary, the form with ra (o) or with ra (29) and the form
with ła () or with ra (9). It was not always easy only with the material collected by him. He had
to decide the matter by additional data in cognate languages like Tamil, Malayalam, Telugu, etc.,
by the methods of comparative and historical linguistics. In such cases he should have written
for instance, *kuri (*7383) instead of kuri (F388) and *kūra (*7809) instead of kūra (793 29) if these
words were not attested in old Kannada, but he did not do it.
A number of dictionaries were prepared by the Kannada scholars in the early 20th century.
The Kannada Sahitya Parishat, an organization for the literary activities in Kannada, got two
dictionaries prepared: one by Rudrayya Mathad 1918 and another by T. Shamanna in 1920. But
they were not published. A well-known writer Shivaram Karant prepared Sirigannada Arthakāśa
in 1940, Gurunath Joshi and Ashvathanarayana published Kannada Kannada Sabdakośa in 1956.
C.E. Kavali published Sacitra Kannada Kannada Kastūri Kāśa in 1957; S. R. Ramarao brought
out Kannada Kannada English Dictionary in 1965.
